³  Part 5  :       Designing your own levels                                  ³
ÀÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÙ

Designing your own levels is a bit complicated since I haven't written a
level editor yet. So what you have to do is to write an ascii-File (in any
ascii-editor you like) that describes the level in the following way:

The level-file must be a collection of blocks. Each block has the following
appearance:

1.   Name of the level - a '*' sign at the beginning denotes a level that
     is directly playable when you enter the game.
2.   Time in seconds
3.   Number of diamonds needed (-1 for all)
4.   Level-data
5.   Endmark @

No blank lines are allowed! Not even at the end of the file...

The following characters are allowed in the level data block:

 x        solid wall (cannot be destroyed)
 -        nonsolid wall (can be destroyed by explosion)
 S        start-position of the player
 E        exit
 blank    empty position
 .        earth
 *        diamond
 o        stone
 U        clock
 B        bomb
 1,2,3,4  monster - the number represents the direction the monster is
          moving at start: 1=left, 2=down, 3=right, 4=up
 5,6,7,8  like the above, but these monsters are converted to diamonds when
          they are destroyed
 :        background bitmap - use this to fill up non-rectangular
          playfields.

Example:

*Intro                            ³ Name of first level is 'Intro'
600                               ³ 600 seconds=6 minutes time
-1                                ³ needed-gems: collect all
xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx               ³ playfield - data
x. *o   ....   ooox               ³
x.o.oo ....  o ..*x               ³ the * in the name *Intro tells the
xSoo ooo* o ox  .*x               ³ program that this level is directly
xxxxxxxxxxxxxx   *x               ³ accessable
xo.  ...ox*...  .*x               ³
xo*... .ox..*. ..*x               ³
xo.  .    ....  .*x               ³
xE  ... *x*.*.   *x               ³
xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx               ³
@                                 ³ <-- don't forget the end mark
Castles                           ³ Name of the second level
240                               ³ Time
10                                ³ 10 diamonds needed
xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx ³
x  3         3        3         x ³ Level-data
x ....   ...................... x ³
x .*..   .xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx. x ³ Since there is not * in front of the
x4....   .xo...*....xoooo...ox. x ³ levelname, the player must solve the
x ....   .x.....*...x......oox. x ³ first level before he can start with
x ..*.  4..........oo......oox.2x ³ this one
x .S..   .xoo.....o.x.o.....ox. x ³
x ....2  .xoo.......x.o....oox. x ³
x ....   .x*........x..o..oo.x. x ³
x .*..   .xxxxxxxxxxxxx.xxxxxx. x ³
x ....  4.x*********xoo...oo.x. x ³
x4....   .x*oo...o.*x*o....oox. x ³
x ....   .x*o....o.*x*o......x.2x ³
x ..*.2  .x*o...ooo*xooo..oo.x. x ³
x ....   .x***********....ooox. x ³
x ....  4.xxxxxxx.xxxxxxxxxxxx. x ³
x ....   .x...  o.x............ x ³
x  1     .xE..oo.ox      1      x ³
xxxxxxxx  xxxxxxxxx  xxxxxxxxxxxx ³
:::::::x             x::::::::::: ³
:::::::xxxxxxxxxxxxxxx::::::::::: ³
@                                 ³ <-- don't forget the end mark, even at
                                        end of the file !!

Remember: no blank lines (make sure there are none at the end of the file)

Possible error messages during level loading:

unreadable timer value:
 There is no number at the position for the time

number of diamonds unknown:
 There is no number at the position for the diamonds

level too large:
 There are more then 50 lines in one level. You probably have forgotten
 an end sign

player start position not found:
 you have forgotten an 'S' indicating the player's start position in the
 level above the specified line.

Ok, this is not at all comfortable but it still has some advantages:
levels can be easily reorderd or copied using your text-editor. The ascii
format is also good for sending levels as email.

After you have written your level-file, say 'levels.dat', you may start
BASH with

 bash levels.dat

This will load the additional levels at the end of the existing ones.
Remember to put a '*' in front of the first level-name in your level-file,
if you want to make this level playable.
